On December 10, 2015, the President signed into law S. 1177, also known as the "Every Student Succeeds Act." This law amends and reauthorizes the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965. Some of the key provisions of the law include: 

1. Requiring states to submit accountability plans that outline achievement goals and school evaluation methods.
2. Requiring states to intervene in under-performing schools.
3. Creating pilot and demonstration programs for new assessment methods and funding allocations.
4. Establishing grant programs that support education innovation, comprehensive services in low-income neighborhoods, and preschool quality and access.
5. Reauthorizing and amending programs for teacher training, Native American education, homeless student assistance, and Federally-connected students.